							              <p>Discovered between 1927 and 1928 at Site-6, near the Mahācaitya, in
								the course of excavations.
								<!-- Note VT, in discussion with AS: There is
                                no clear provenance for this piece, and the only reason for which it
                                has been attached to site 1 is the mention of the Mahācetiya in l.
                                2. There is however, a problem of circularity in the reasoning that
                                have grouped all inscriptions mentioning the Mahācetiya under the
                                assumption that they are connected to site 1, before using the
                                epigraphic reference to contend that no other Cetiya at the site was
                                called a Mahācetiya. Hence, the reasoning put forward in Rosen Stone
                                1994: 24-31, to suggest that the Mahācetiya might—in spite of
                                Longhurst’s report according to which no sculpture had been found
                                from site 1—have been adorned, bearing at least āyaka frises such as
                                NM 592 (= EIAD 80) appears particularly weak. On stylistic grounds
                                (see in particular the rows of three vertical lotuses that separate
                                each register and the rows of birds and pearls running on the lower
                                part of the frise), in terms of dimensions (with H = 33 to 33.5 cm
                                in both EIAD 80, and 81 + 90, the latter of which certainly belong
                                to site 6), there is good argument to link this particular piece to
                                site 6 as well. The paleography and the phraseology of the two
                                inscriptions is also very similar, which strengthens the argument.
                                If this reasoning is acceptable, then this would have implications
                                for our understanding of the site, since this would suggest that
                                stūpa no. 6 might have been called a Mahācetiya before or along with
                                site 1. -->
							</p>
